Note: In dark-field observation, the solution reacted with the target DNA is dropped onto the silicon wafer for observation. Without prior dilution, too many nanoprobes present in the solution will stack on the silicon wafer, and the dense nanoprobes greatly increase the possibility of their proximity. In this protocol, particles with different aggregation states are distinguished by their different scattered light. However, the existence of the above situation will make some single particles mistakenly emit scattered light of aggregates, which is unfavorable for distinguishing particles with different aggregation states. Meanwhile, the protocol uses a lot of statistical analysis. In order to improve the efficiency of image analysis, dilution of the solution is also necessary.
Put the dried slide glass on the stage, adjust the lens focus, and perform dark field imaging.
