For image processing, use the following ImageJ code:
/∗∗
∗ This is an ImageJ macro for analyzing dark-field plasmonic imaging results
∗ ImageJ Version: 1.52p
∗/
// set parameters for analyzing
// threshold ∼ [prominence, hue, sat, intensity] ∼ for noise elimination
prominence_threshold = 20;
//hue_threshold = 150; // 0∼360
//saturation_threshold = 0.1; // 0∼1
//intensity_threshold = 30; // 0∼255
//threshold = newArray(prominence_threshold,hue_threshold,saturation_threshold,intensity_threshold);
main();
// main process definition
function main(){

// threshold ∼ [prominence, hue, sat, intensity]
  img = getTitle();
  fpath = getDirectory("image");
  selectWindow(img);
  t1 = 0; t2 = 0; t3 = 0;
  locs = pFinder(prominence_threshold); // set the prominence of particles
  n = lengthOf(locs)/2;
  for(i=0;i<n;i++){
    x = locs[2∗i]; y = locs[2∗i+1];
    hsi = getHSI(x,y);
    ptype = judge(hsi);
    if (ptype==1) t1++;
    else if (ptype==2) t2++;
    else if (ptype==3) t3++;
    setResult("X",i,x);
    setResult("Y",i,y);
    setResult("Type",i,ptype);
    setResult("Hue",i,hsi[0]);
    setResult("Sat",i,hsi[1]);
    setResult("Int",i,hsi[2]);
  }
  setResult("count1",0,t1);
  setResult("count2",0,t2);
  setResult("count3",0,t3);
  updateResults();
  drawParticles(img);
  selectWindow("Results");
  saveAs("results",fpath+img+"_particles.csv");
  run("Close");
  selectWindow(img);
  saveAs("png",fpath+img+"_redraw.png");
  // close();
}
// self-defined functions
function judge(hsi){
  // hue: 0∼360, sat: 0∼1, intensity: 0∼255
  // threshold ∼ [prominence, hue, sat, intensity]
  // return ptype: 0∼noise, 1∼single, 2∼small cluster, 3∼large cluster
  h = hsi[0]; s = hsi[1]; i = hsi[2];
  if (i<40&&i>235) return 0;
  else if (s<0.1) return 0;
  else if (h>160&&h<340) return 0;
  else if (h>62) return 1;
  else if (h>30) return 2;
  else return 3;
}
function drawParticles(img){
  // particle analysis results window is required!
  colors = newArray("#3f4470","#43a123","#f2b211","#ff0000"); // [noise, single, small cluster, large cluster]
  size = newArray(7,5,5,5);
  selectWindow(img);
  n = nResults;
  for(i=0;i<n;i++){
    x = getResult("X",i); y = getResult("Y",i); ptype = getResult("Type",i);
    c = colors[ptype];
    setColor(c);
    s = size[ptype];
    fillRect(x-s,y-s,4∗s,4∗s);
  }
}
function pFinder(h){
  // find all particles by bultin ImageJ function and return their locations
  run("Find Maxima...", "prominence="+h+" strict output=[List]");
  selectWindow("Results");
  locs = newArray(2∗nResults);
  for(i=0;i<nResults;i++){
    locs[2∗i]=getResult("X",i);
    locs[2∗i+1]=getResult("Y",i);
  }
  run("Close");
  return locs;
}
function getHSI(x,y){
    rgb = getRGB(x,y);
    HSI = RGB2HSI(rgb);
    return HSI;
}
function getRGB(x,y){
    RGB = newArray(3);
    v = getPixel(x,y);
    RGB[0] = (v>>16)&0xff; // extract red byte (bits 23-17)
    RGB[1] = (v>>8)&0xff; // extract green byte (bits 15-8)
    RGB[2] = v&0xff; // extract blue byte (bits 7-0)
    return RGB;
}
function RGB2HSI(rgb){
    r = rgb[0]; // red
    g = rgb[1]; // green
  b = rgb[2]; // blue 0∼255
  num = 0.5∗((r-g)+(r-b));
  den = sqrt((r-g)∗(r-g)+(r-b)∗(g-b));
  theta = acos(num/(den+1e-6));
  h = theta;

if (b>g) h = 2∗PI - theta;
  h = h/(2∗PI);
  Array.getStatistics(rgb, min, max, mean, stdDev);
  den = r+g+b;
  if (den==0) den = 1e-6;
  s = 1-3∗min/den;
  if (s==0) h = 0;
  i = mean;
  h = h∗360;
    HSI = newArray(h,s,i);
    return HSI;
}
Note: After ImageJ code conversion, particles in different aggregation states can be more clearly distinguished (Figure 7[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig7]C), and can be statistically classified by hue and saturation (Figure 7[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig7]D).
Raman sensing performance
Timing: 4 h
In this step, in order to test the Raman sensing performance of nanoprobes, reproducibility, single-stranded target DNA comparison and specificity experiments are carried out.
Fix a silicon wafer on the slide.
Soak it in freshly prepared aqua regia for 30 min in the fume hood, rinse with ultrapure water, dry for later use.
After the target DNA bind with the two nanoprobes, drop the solution on the silicon wafer for SERS measurement.
Note: After the solution drops onto the silicon wafer, it is better to wait for it to dry before measuring, because the presence of liquid will affect the focus of SERS measurement. The solution dropped can be reduced to accelerate the drying process. Try to avoid using the high temperature of oven, which may lead to the aggregation of particle.
Note: The measurement parameters: excitation light wavelength is 785 nm, laser power is 25 mW, integration time is 10 s, scanning times are 3 times, 20× objective lens is used, and each group of experiments is repeated 3 times.
For the reproducibility experiment, test the SERS signals of 30 target DNA randomly (Figure 8[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig8]A).
